#Text=THE JAIL-BREAKERS
#Text=For a long time it had been arranged they all should go to the Harvard and Yale game in Winthrop 's car .
#Text=It was perfectly well understood .
#Text=Even Peabody , who pictured himself and Miss Forbes in the back of the car , with her brother and Winthrop in front , condescended to approve .
#Text=It was necessary to invite Peabody because it was his great good fortune to be engaged to Miss Forbes .

#Text=Her brother Sam had been invited , not only because he could act as chaperon for his sister , but because since they were at St. Paul 's , Winthrop and he , either as participants or spectators , had never missed going together to the Yale-Harvard game .
#Text=And Beatrice Forbes herself had been invited because she was herself .
#Text=When at nine o'clock on the morning of the game , Winthrop stopped the car in front of her door , he was in love with all the world .
#Text=In the November air there was a sting like frost-bitten cider , in the sky there was a brilliant , beautiful sun , in the wind was the tingling touch of three ice-chilled rivers .

#Text=And in the big house facing Central Park , outside of which his prancing steed of brass and scarlet chugged and protested and trembled with impatience , was the most wonderful girl in all the world .
#Text=It was true she was engaged to be married , and not to him .
#Text=But she was not yet married .

#Text=And to-day it would be his privilege to carry her through the State of New York and the State of Connecticut , and he would snatch glimpses of her profile rising from the rough fur collar , of her wind-blown hair , of the long , lovely lashes under the gray veil .
#Text="

#Text=' Shall be together , breathe and ride , so , one day more am I deified ; '  whispered the young man in the Scarlet Car ;

column1: #Text=As he waited at the curb , other great touring-cars , of every speed and shape , in the mad race for the Boston Post Road , and the town of New Haven , swept up Fifth Avenue .
#Text=Some rolled and puffed like tugboats in a heavy seaway , others glided by noiseless and proud as private yachts .
#Text=But each flew the colors of blue or crimson .
#Text=Winthrop 's car , because her brother had gone to one college , and he had played right end for the other , was draped impartially .
#Text=And so every other car mocked or cheered it , and in one a bare-headed youth stood up , and shouted to his fellows : " Look !

#Text=That she also wore her automobile coat caused the heart of Winthrop to leap hopefully .
#Text=" Winthrop , " said Peabody , " I am in rather an embarrassing position .

#Text= Do I understand , Beatrice , " began Peabody in a tone that instantly made every one extremely uncomfortable , " that I am to tell my sister you are not coming ? "

column1: #Text=" Ernest ! " begged Miss Forbes .
#Text=Winthrop bent hastily over the oil valves .
#Text=He read the speedometer , which was , as usual , out of order , with fascinated interest .
#Text=" Ernest , " pleaded Miss Forbes ,
#Text=" Mr. Winthrop and Sam planned this trip for us a long time ago -- to give us a little pleasure -- -- "
#Text=" Then , " said Peabody in a hollow voice , " you have decided ? "
#Text=" Ernest , " cried Miss Forbes , " do n't look at me as though you meant to hurl the curse of Rome .

#Text= I will bid you good-by , " said Peabody ; " I have only just time to catch our train . "

column1: #Text=Miss Forbes rose and moved to the door of the car .
#Text=" I had better not go with any one , " she said in a low voice .
#Text=" You will go with me , " commanded her brother .
#Text=" Come on , Ernest . "
#Text=" Thank you , no , " replied Peabody .
#Text=" I have promised my sister . "
#Text=" All right , then , " exclaimed Sam briskly , " see you at the game .
